					<head>Pentateuch</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79066420" rend="visible">
						<summary>Pentateuch, Hafṭarot and Five Scrolls, provided with punctuation, accents, masorah magna and parva. Aka the 'London Catalan Pentateuch'.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79066420">
							<locus from="1r" to="248v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Torah, megilot ṿe-hafṭarot</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">תורה, מגילות  והפטרות </title>
							<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
							<note>
								<p>Masoretic rubrics registering the numbers of verses, centre-mark, number of pericopes and sedarim, are found at the end of the last four books of the Pentateuch. A similar rubric for the whole Pentateuch is given at the end of Deuteronomy.</p>
							</note>
							<decoNote type="paratext">Numerous micrographical designs. </decoNote>
							<decoNote type="marginal">Numerous decorated parashah signs, in ink.</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="illustration">
								<locus n="1r"/>Pen-drawing of a castle (on a doodle-page).</decoNote>
							<filiation>The mansucript is considered to be the first volume of the series completed by Harley 5574 and Harley 5575, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">121</ref>, which are similar, though not identical in style of writing.</filiation>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="1v" to="42v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Genesis</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="42v" to="80r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Exodus</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="80r" to="106r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Leviticus</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="106r" to="141r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Numbers</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="141r" to="172r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Deuteronomy</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="172r" to="225r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Hafṭarot  </title>
								<note>
									<p>Contains Hafṭarot for the whole year.</p>
									<p>The Hafṭarah for the pericope ויהי ביום is placed last, with the following note at the end: <q>בעבור ששכחתי מלכתוב אותה במקומה כתכתיה כאן</q>.</p>
								</note>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="225r" to="227v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Ruth</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="227v" to="230r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Song of Songs</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="230r" to="236r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Ecclesiastes</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="236r" to="239v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Lamentations</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="239v" to="248v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Esther</title>
							</msItem>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of late 14th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<extent rend="visible">248 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>220</height>
										<width>170</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>140</height>
										<width>120</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>248 folios (+ 2 unfoliated modern paper flyleaves and 2 foliated older paper flyleaves [folios 1* and 2*] at the beginning and 2 unfoliated older flyleaves and 2 unfoliated modern paper flyleaves at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>32 quires: i-xv8 (folios 1-120), xvi10+2 (folios 121-132), xvii10 (folios 133-142), xviii-xx10 (folios 143-162), xxi-xxiii6 (folios 163-172), xxiv9 (folios 179-187), xxv10-2 (folios 188-195), xxvi8 (folios 196-203), xxvii-xxxi8 (folios 204-243), xxxii5 (folios 244-248).</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2" ruledLines="25" writtenLines="25">
									<p>Watermark, folios [249] and [250], of a fleur-de-lis in a crowned coat of arms and with the monogram 'WR', similar to <ref target="Heawood_1950" type="number">1784</ref>.
</p>
									<p>2 unfoliated blank leaves after folio 171.
</p>
									<p>Ruling with hard point and sometimes pricking are visible.</p>
									<p>The masorah (only in the Pentateuch) occupies two lines in the upper and three lines in the lower margin.</p>
									<p>In the Pentateuch a new pericope is marked by פרש' sometimes decorated in pen and ink.</p>
									<p>Ornamental חזק written at the end of Genesis.</p>
									<p>Leviticus and Esther begin a new column, and the Hafṭarot open a new leaf.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc>
							<summary>Sefardi square script, punctuated, of the last quarter of the 14th century.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<decoDesc>
							<summary>Numerous micrographical designs. Numerous decorated parashah signs, in ink. Pen drawing of a castle.</summary>
							<decoNote type="paratext">Numerous micrographical designs. </decoNote>
							<decoNote type="marginal">Numerous decorated parashah signs, in ink.</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="illustration">
								<locus n="1"/>Pen-drawing of a castle.</decoNote>
						</decoDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Italian inscription stating that this is the first volume of a three-volume Bible and that it was written in 'Castion' in mese Elul in anno <date calendar="Hebrew">5105 </date> (<date calendar="Gregorian">1345</date>) e la scrittura di Ezra figlio di Jacob Adorat (these data correspond with the colophon in Harley 5775, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">121</ref>,([2v]). </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. 'Harleian' binding of black buckram.</p>
								<p>Boxed.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1375" notAfter="1399"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>Spain, N. E. (<name type="place">Catalonia</name>)</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">John Covel</name> (b. 1638, d. 1722), chaplain to the Levant Company at <name type="place">Constantinople</name>: in his collection (no. VIII.): inscribed (<locus n="fs003r">[1r]</locus>). His manuscripts were acquired for the Harley Collection for £300 in 1716; Latin inscription: <q>de accurate Bibliorum Hebrais</q>. .. (18th century?).
</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name>: bought by him together with Covel's other manuscripts, for £300 on <date calendar="Gregorian">27 February 1715/6</date> (<ref target="Wright_1972"/>). The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts.
Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date>to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
					</history>
